---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Hero from "@/components/Hero.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import { breadcrumbList } from "@/lib/schema";

const title = "About AffiliateTools.co — How This Review Desk Works";
const description =
  "What AffiliateTools.co covers, why it exists, and the editorial standards behind the site.";
const canonical = "/about/";

const jsonLd = [
  breadcrumbList([
    { name: "Home", path: "/" },
    { name: "About", path: "/about/" },
  ]),
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonical={canonical}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <section class="container-max" style="padding: 1.5rem 1.25rem 0;">
    <Breadcrumb items={[{ name: "Home", href: "/" }, { name: "About" }]} />
  </section>

  <Hero
    eyebrow="About AffiliateTools.co"
    title="The honest review site for affiliate marketer software."
    sub="We review the software affiliate marketers actually run — starting with ad spy tools. The focus is practical coverage, transparent methodology, and buyer-useful conclusions."
  />

  <article class="container-prose" style="padding: 2rem 1.25rem 4rem;">
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Who we are</h2>
      <p>
        AffiliateTools.co is an editorial review desk focused on the software
        affiliate marketers actually use. The goal is simple: publish specific,
        tested, readable coverage instead of generic "top 10" filler.
      </p>
      <p>
        We built AffiliateTools.co because affiliate marketers couldn't find
        honest tool reviews. Every other site in this category fell into one of
        two buckets: pay-for-play listicles where every tool is "the best," or
        thinly-disguised marketing funnels with no real testing. Both failure
        modes produce the same useless outcome for the buyer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our editorial framing is simple: <strong
          >we're affiliate marketers first</strong
        >. We know the difference between a ClickBank creative and a DTC
        e-commerce ad. We know why days-running matters more than impressions
        for CPA research. And we know when a tool is genuinely useful versus
        when it's just marketing the category.
      </p>

      <h2>Why we started</h2>
      <p>
        In early 2026 we spent two weeks reading reviews, watching walkthroughs,
        and signing up for trials across the ad-intelligence category. The
        experience was frustrating:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Most "top 10" lists ranked tools based on affiliate commissions, not
          product quality.
        </li>
        <li>Prices were often outdated by 6+ months.</li>
        <li>
          Platform coverage was routinely overstated. Several tools claimed
          "TikTok support" that turned out to be a thin API wrapper around the
          TikTok Creative Center — not first-party ad tracking.
        </li>
        <li>
          Features we needed (landing page archival, affiliate-network
          classification, creative grouping across advertisers) weren't
          discussed anywhere because most review sites don't understand
          affiliate marketing.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        So we decided to write the site we wished existed. AffiliateTools.co
        ships with <strong>7 detailed ad spy tool reviews</strong>, <strong
          >21 head-to-head comparisons</strong
        >, and <strong>six flagship listicles</strong>, with more on the way.
        Every review is written to surface real tradeoffs. Every price is dated.
        Every marketing claim is attributed.
      </p>

      <h2>Our editorial guardrails</h2>
      <p>
        Review sites only earn trust when the standards are visible. We try to
        compensate for the category's usual bias problems in three ways:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Structural honesty.</strong> Reviews and versus pages lead with
          the strongest arguments for the tool being evaluated. Comparison tables
          are built to show tradeoffs, not just wins.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Open methodology.</strong> Our <a href="/methodology/"
            >methodology page</a
          > documents the eight dimensions we score each tool on, how we weight those
          dimensions for different listicle intents, and how we verify competitor
          pricing. You can audit our work.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Scope discipline.</strong> We would rather be obviously deep in
          one category than pretend broad coverage exists before it does. If a tool
          fits a narrow use case, that is how it gets presented.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        That means the winner changes with the use case. The TikTok ad spy tools
        list favors <a href="/ad-spy-tools/pipiads-review/">PiPiADS</a>. The
        dropshipping coverage leans toward <a href="/ad-spy-tools/minea-review/"
          >Minea</a
        >. The free-tier coverage points readers to <a
          href="/ad-spy-tools/bigspy-review/">BigSpy</a
        >. The point is fit, not forcing one answer everywhere.
      </p>

      <h2>What we review</h2>
      <p>
        Today: <strong>ad spy and ad intelligence tools</strong>. Seven tools in
        depth — AdRecon, AdSpy, BigSpy, PowerAdSpy, Foreplay, Minea, PiPiADS —
        plus head-to-head comparisons and ranked listicles covering the queries
        affiliate marketers actually search for ("adspy alternatives", "best ad
        spy tools for ClickBank", "best free ad spy tool", etc.).
      </p>
      <p>Planned next 12 months:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Landing page builders</strong> — ClickFunnels, Systeme.io, Leadpages,
          Unbounce, Instapage, scored against affiliate marketer use cases.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Affiliate networks</strong> — ClickBank, Digistore24, BuyGoods,
          MaxWeb, WarriorPlus, MoreNiche, and regional networks.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Tracking platforms</strong> — Voluum, RedTrack, Binom, FunnelFlux,
          ClickMagick, Everflow.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Email marketing tools</strong> — Beehiiv, ConvertKit, Klaviyo, targeted
          at affiliate email monetization.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>CRO tools</strong> — heat maps, session recording, A/B testing for
          affiliate funnels.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you're an affiliate operator with strong opinions on what we should
        cover next, email us.
      </p>

      <h2>Editorial policies</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Affiliate links.</strong> For v1, this site contains zero affiliate
          links. We are intentionally keeping the site editorial-first rather than
          filling it with product CTAs. If we add affiliate links to competitor tools
          in the future, we will disclose them with <code>rel="sponsored"</code> and
          a visible label.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Paid placements.</strong> We do not accept paid rankings or sponsored
          "best of" placements. Tools are not removable from listicles in exchange
          for payment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Corrections.</strong> Email <a
            href="mailto:hello@affiliatetools.co">hello@affiliatetools.co</a
          > with corrections. We publish corrections openly — no silent edits.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Fact verification.</strong> Pricing is verified quarterly. Feature
          claims are verified annually. Every page shows the "Updated" date in the
          hero.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Competitor claims.</strong> Marketing claims made by competitors
          (e.g., "200M+ ads indexed") are cited as claims, never stated as facts.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to reach us</h2>
      <p>
        The fastest way to reach us is email: <a
          href="mailto:hello@affiliatetools.co">hello@affiliatetools.co</a
        >.
      </p>
      <p>
        For corrections, pricing updates, partnership inquiries, or tip-offs
        about something we missed, use the same address. See the <a
          href="/contact/">contact page</a
        > for which channel to use for what.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
